<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-01-27T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-01-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="200" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d200">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/827: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Sterling</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-27T12:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">January
                                            27, 1922—noon</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received 1:45
                                    p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>2. The Minister for Foreign Affairs is ready to withdraw the reply of
                                the Peruvian Government, the translation of which was sent to you in
                                my 96, January 19, 7 p.m. and to replace it with another one in the
                                exact terms of the first note but omitting the words “ajustado por
                                el gobierno de los Estados Unidos (adjusted by the Government of the
                                United States).” Is this satisfactory? Rush reply.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Sterling</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>